Gymnodamaeus bicostatus
: 
Kulczynski 1902

; 
Sellnick 1928
; 
Willmann 1931
; 
Grandjean 1954
; 
Sellnick 1960
; 
Kunst 1971
; 
Bulanova-Zachvatkina 1975
; 
Marshall et al. 1987
; 
Woas 1992
; 
Pérez-Íñigo 1997
; 
Subías 2004
; 
Weigmann 2006
; 
Weigmann and Mourek 2008
.

Gymnodamaeus bicostatus

is considered to have a holarctic distribution (
Subías 2004
; 
Weigmann 2006
) and a microphytophagous feeding style (
Schuster 1956
; 
Schatz 1996
). It inhabits dry steppe soil in East 
Tyrol
(
Austria
) and has been considered a xerophilic species (
Mihelčič 1964
; 
Schatz 1996
), but 
Schuster (1960)
considered its preference to be for moderately dry and moderately fresh habitats. 
Rajski (1967)
found this species in 
Dicrano-Pinetum
and 
Querco-Carpinetum
forest associations, with preference for acid soils. In central Europe this species inhabits dry and warm forest floor, mosses and lichens, and even lives arboreally (
Weigmann 2006
), but probably has wide tolerance to temperature (
Weigmann and Mourek 2008
).
